Value.value: *The old man seems distracted looking north into the valley* Oh! Um... This is not good, not good at all.

*sighs heavily* You have to help me. There are giant creatures that look like spiders inside a cavern to the north here. I lost my medicine last time I wandered close, think it got stuck in the hive mother's web.
Won't you go and retrieve it for me? Should be stuck with her. You can keep her silk, but bring me my medicine back please.
Be careful of her venom and her stalking tactics. You'll get a reward, of course! *he rummages in a bag* I have a bit of gold I can offer you when you retrieve it.
Yes! That! That's my medicine. *goes about taking the "medicine" and putting it in a pipe to smoke it, and then retrieves the promised gold* Thank you a million times, I couldn't sleep without this!
*a heavy sigh, tears in his eyes* You have not retrieved my medicine yet? I need it. Please! Please get it for me from the valley north of here.
Thank you for getting my medicine for me! If you head to the west coast from here and then south to Moonpier, you can likely find some work there.

A long staff of twisting oak, one in four matching of its kind. The wood originally a fallen branch from the duir, is etched with runic marks that give off a healthy glow you'd expect. They seem to aid in a process of channelling life energy through staves, twisted roots wind around the base in a manner that provides for better gripping, intertwining and sealing into the very end one small sapphire gemstone.  

This is indeed a living weapon, sprouting small buds in the spring and loosing the few leaves that occasionally sprout from it when the colder months are upon it. The staff slowly recharges itself like any plant by exposure to sun and water. 

Having been specifically shed and embued these branches for the selected druid elders, each maintains a perfect display of balance in the abilities it grants the user. In addition, it summons one protector of each of four elements for the druids that the staves deem worthy.

This small shrub is easily recognizable as a sweetbush.  Growing anywhere from 3-6 feet in height, this type of bush is often sought after by small children.  The berries have an overly sweet taste that most adult folk find overpowering, yet children delight in the fruit.  This particular bush is still young, and needs care.

The Sweetberry is a highly prized item for Cordorian children, to others, completely useless.  Commonly stuck on the end of a stick and licked, the sweetberry has a powerfully sweet taste that most adults find overwhelming.  Except in Amia, where they are enjoyed by almost all, sometimes even a little too much, in the case of an ex-assassin who craves them with a passion.

The fence is a thick hedge of thorny growth, walls of tearing thorns have risen out of the forest ground to give the grove extra protection it requires. // OOC note: If you are not a druid of at least five levels you should not use the following information in your RP//  These barriers are permanent or temporary, depending on the wishes of a cleric of Silvanus. Preformed with a divine spell titled Thorncall, a ritual magic that occurs when a servant of Silvanus has been slain or shed much blood in the vicinity, though a servitor creature such as a stag may be substituted. The Thorncall ritual is typically used to keep out those who would burn or despoil the forest in such a way as to upset the Balance.
You can take a tiny chip of this crystal and use it as a lens in your porting wand.

To the West: Moonpier, Fort Cystana

Ivy grows on this thick stone tablet. You can see words engraved in the stone.

"Nature's blessings upon ye who enter the Oakmist Vale. Friends of the woods are welcomed with open arms, but know that ye who violate against our hospitality shall face the fury of the Wild.

Cover not yer face with helms or cloths

Bear nay arms within our grove

Ye shan't take forms of any monstrous beasts, such as the minotaurs or dragons.

Undeath is an affront to the natural cycle and shan't be tolerated in any form.

Drow, aberrations, fiend-kin, goblinoid and chromatic dragonblooded or disciples are not welcome, unless they were granted permission by the archdruids."
